<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-306-346  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 306 346.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 2 1990 v12 n14 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Font wars' need to consider user's view. (congruency of screendisplay and printed output)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coale, Kristi.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Font vendors say that the so-called 'wars' overcomputer-typography technology will ultimately benefit users byreducing font prices, but the issues involved in creating WYSIWYGoutput on both display screens and printers are complex.andP;  A fonttechnology describes how text is displayed on either the computerscreen or printed page, while a page description languageencompasses both text and graphic images.andP;  PostScript, the firstdevice-independent font system, is a complete page descriptionlanguage.andP;  It encompasses the Adobe Type 1 font format, whichcontains outline and 'hinting' information along with rasterizercode for converting character outlines into bit maps.andP;  Apple'sTrue Image page description language includes is True Type fonttechnology.andP;  Outline fonts are described mathematically as linesand Bezier curves rather than bit maps and lets users scale fontsto any size without producing 'jagged' lines.andP;  True Type is anopen technology that will be compatible with PostScript and isunlikely to upset the congruence of outline printer and displayfonts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     WYSIWYGFontsI-O ManagementDesktop PublishingDevice IndependenceCompetitionTypesetting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>